name: xsrv
description:
Run your own network services, on a server you control.

This ansible playbook lets you quickly and reliably install and manage various network services and applications on your own servers. A simple command-line wrapper is provided for initial deployment and occasional maintenance tasks.
contribution_justification: https://gitlab.com/nodiscc/xsrv#contributingissueswork-in-progress
license_location_justification: https://gitlab.com/nodiscc/xsrv/-/blob/master/LICENSE
floss_license_justification: The GPL-3.0-only license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The GPL-3.0-only license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: https://gitlab.com/nodiscc/xsrv/
build_common_tools_justification: The playbook only uses make, bash and python virtualenv/pip to bootstrap a working environment.
build_floss_tools_justification: All software installed by the playbook, the deployment software, and the base operating system are Free and Open Source Software
test_most_justification:
The test suite should check for correct execution and idempotence automatically against a simulation environment.
All role variables should be checked for existence and proper type before running the role.
warnings_fixed_justification:
All warnings produced by automated checks are addressed https://gitlab.com/nodiscc/xsrv/-/pipelines
All warnings produced by ansible at runtime are addessed.
warnings_strict_justification:
All exceptions to automated checks are documented, implemented only when necessary (compatibility), and reviewed regularly.
All warnings in implemented services are forwarded to the user through monitoring and generate alarms.
TODO count number of exceptions to ansible-lint (noqa) and shellcheck ignore rules, print a warning during tests
crypto_published_justification: No cleartext sensitive values are stored on the controller by default. Provided services only use strong cryptography over the network when possible.
crypto_call_justification: Uses cryptographic tools provided by ansible and openssl
crypto_keylength_justification: ansible-vault uses AES256. network services are configured to use 2048-bit keys or longer (SSH, HTTPS...)
crypto_working_justification: Broken algorithms are disabled when possible in services configuration.
crypto_pfs_justification: Check that all installed services are configured for Perfect Forward Secrecy
crypto_password_storage_justification: Review all installed applications/services source code, and check that they correctly implement password hashing/storage.
delivery_mitm_justification: All software downloaded over git/ssh, https or http with cryptographic signature verification.
delivery_unsigned_justification: All hashes/checksums validated against GPG signatures.
static_analysis_justification: Syntax checks and linters documented in Makefile
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: The project is mostly configuration, does not apply. ansible-lint looks for possibly insecure settings on file permissions (undefined/default). The common role applies balanced hardening measures and ensures daily Debian packages security upgrades, the monitoring role is able to alert on various security-related indicators. 3rd-party software versions are upgraded as soon as possible after announcement through their releases RSS feed.
static_analysis_fixed_justification: Patches issued as soon as possible after discovered, best-effort; last occurence: fixed in ~24h https://github.com/nodiscc/xsrv/commit/bc3c07428b52a8a15f0f942d7e62877adcf0a408 after ansible-lint 4.3 starts reporting problematic file permissions.
static_analysis_often_justification: Static analysis triggered on every commit: https://gitlab.com/nodiscc/xsrv/-/pipelines
discussion_justification: https://gitlab.com/nodiscc/xsrv/issues
hardened_site_justification: Found all required security hardening headers.
